        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Explicit local intent</strong> occurs when a search query directly includes a geographic modifier — such as a city name, neighborhood, zip code, or "near me" — leaving no ambiguity about the searcher wanting geographically relevant results. These queries represent the most conversion-ready searches in local SEO and consistently trigger local pack and Google Maps results.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Near me growth</div>
            <div class="tms-value">500%+ over recent years</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">SERP features triggered</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local Pack + Maps</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Someone searching "best Thai restaurant in Seattle" has already made a location decision. They're not browsing — they're choosing. Explicit local intent queries are the final step before a customer walks in the door or calls your number. Ranking here is where local SEO converts to revenue.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is explicit local intent?</h2>
        <p>Explicit local intent is one of two categories of local search intent (the other being implicit local intent). The distinction is whether the geographic signal is stated or inferred:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Explicit local intent:</strong> "plumber in Austin" — the location is stated directly in the query</li>
          <li><strong>Implicit local intent:</strong> "plumber" — no location stated, but Google infers the searcher wants nearby results based on device location and query context</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Geographic modifiers that create explicit local intent include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>City names: "dentist Dallas," "coffee shop Portland"</li>
          <li>Neighborhood names: "yoga studio Brooklyn," "pizza Shoreditch"</li>
          <li>Zip or postal codes: "personal injury lawyer 77002"</li>
          <li>"Near me" and variants: "near me," "nearby," "close to me"</li>
          <li>Landmarks: "hotel near Eiffel Tower," "restaurant near Wembley"</li>
          <li>State or region: "ski resort Colorado," "vineyard Napa Valley"</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google data — near me search growth</div>
          <p>According to Google Think, <strong>searches containing "near me" have grown over 500%</strong> in recent years, with mobile devices driving the majority of explicit local queries. Local intent now appears in more than 46% of all Google searches (BrightLocal, 2024 Local Search Consumer Report).</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why explicit local intent matters for local businesses</h2>
        <p>Explicit local queries are the most commercially valuable search type for businesses with a physical presence or local service area. Here is why:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Highest purchase intent.</strong> A searcher who types "emergency plumber Austin" has an immediate need and a location decision already made. Conversion rates from explicit local queries consistently exceed general keyword traffic by 3-5x in local service industries.</li>
          <li><strong>Local pack priority.</strong> Explicit local queries reliably trigger Google's local pack — the 3-business map result that appears above organic listings. Ranking in the local pack for explicit queries drives calls, directions requests, and website clicks at rates organic ranking cannot match.</li>
          <li><strong>Content targeting precision.</strong> Because the geographic entity is stated, you can create dedicated pages for each service-location combination that exactly match the query. This is harder to do for implicit queries where intent must be inferred.</li>
          <li><strong>Consistent across devices.</strong> Explicit local queries perform consistently on desktop, mobile, and voice — because the geographic signal is in the words, not dependent on device location data.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google processes explicit local intent queries</h2>
        <p>When Google receives an explicit local query, it follows a specific processing sequence:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Geographic entity extraction:</strong> Google identifies the location signal — city name, "near me" (resolves to GPS coordinates), zip code, or landmark — and uses it as a geographic bounding box for results.</li>
          <li><strong>Relevance matching:</strong> Google matches businesses to the query using GBP category, website content, and keyword signals. "Plumber in Austin" returns plumbing businesses, not general contractors.</li>
          <li><strong>Distance calculation:</strong> For city-name queries, Google measures distance from business location to the named city center. For "near me" queries, it measures from the device's GPS coordinates.</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence ranking:</strong> Among businesses that pass the relevance and distance filters, Google ranks by prominence — review count, review score, citation consistency, backlinks, and overall authority signals.</li>
        </ol>

