        <h2 id="examples">Real explicit local intent examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Service business targeting city-name queries</h3>
        <p>An Austin HVAC company creates individual service pages targeting "AC repair Austin," "furnace installation Austin," and "HVAC maintenance Cedar Park" (a neighboring city). Each page includes local references, technician service area maps, and Austin-specific testimonials. The result: top-3 local pack positions for 12 city-modified queries within 6 months.</p>

        <h3>2. Legal firm targeting zip code queries</h3>
        <p>A Houston personal injury firm builds landing pages for high-value zip codes in their service area: <code>/personal-injury-lawyer-77002/</code>, <code>/personal-injury-lawyer-77004/</code>. Each page references landmarks and neighborhoods within the zip code and includes zip-specific Google reviews. Organic + maps traffic from these pages accounts for 35% of total inbound leads.</p>

        <h3>3. Restaurant targeting "near me" optimization</h3>
        <p>A Thai restaurant in Seattle ensures their Google Business Profile has complete categories, updated hours, 200+ reviews with "Thai food Seattle" mentioned naturally in review text, and photos geotagged to the restaurant address. Result: appearing in local pack for "best Thai restaurant Seattle," "Thai food near me," and "Thai restaurant Capitol Hill."</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Explicit local intent vs implicit local intent</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Explicit local intent</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Geographic modifier stated in query</li>
              <li>"plumber in Austin," "dentist 77002," "pizza near me"</li>
              <li>Higher purchase intent — location already decided</li>
              <li>Targeted with location landing pages + GBP</li>
              <li>Consistent across devices and locations</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Implicit local intent</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>No location stated — Google infers it</li>
              <li>"plumber," "pizza delivery," "oil change"</li>
              <li>Moderate intent — Google guesses local is relevant</li>
              <li>Targeted primarily through GBP prominence</li>
              <li>Varies by device location, changes if searcher moves</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for ranking on explicit local intent queries</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Create dedicated location + service pages.</strong> One page per service-city combination: <code>/plumbing-services-austin/</code>, <code>/plumbing-services-cedar-park/</code>. Each page needs unique content, not just a swapped city name.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimize your Google Business Profile for explicit keywords.</strong> Include service categories and location-specific terms in your GBP description, services list, and post content — GBP signals drive local pack ranking.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn reviews that mention location keywords naturally.</strong> Reviews containing "best plumber in Austin" carry keyword-and-location signals directly into your GBP. Encourage satisfied customers to mention the city in reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Build local citations with consistent NAP.</strong> Name, Address, Phone number consistency across directories (Yelp, Angi, BBB, industry directories) reinforces your location signal for explicit queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Add structured data with location markup.</strong> Use <code>LocalBusiness</code> schema with <code>addressLocality</code>, <code>geo</code> coordinates, and <code>areaServed</code> to make your location explicit to crawlers, not just visible in page text.</li>
          <li><strong>Target neighborhood-level modifiers for urban markets.</strong> "Coffee shop Brooklyn" is less competitive than "coffee shop New York" and converts better because it's more specific. Map your service area to neighborhoods, not just cities.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor query performance by geography in Search Console.</strong> Filter by queries containing city names to see which explicit local terms you're appearing for, your average position, and CTR — then prioritize content gaps.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — thin location pages</div>
          <p>Creating 50 city pages where only the city name changes is a Panda-era trap. Google identifies and demotes thin, near-duplicate location pages. Each location page must contain genuinely unique content: local service area description, area-specific customer examples, neighborhood references, and locally relevant FAQs. If you can't write 500 unique words about a location, don't create a page for it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common explicit local intent mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring neighborhood-level targeting</strong> — sub-city geographic modifiers often have less competition and higher conversion rates than city-wide terms.</li>
          <li><strong>Failing to claim and optimize Google Business Profile</strong> — GBP is the primary ranking signal for local pack results; no profile means no local pack visibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the wrong service area in GBP</strong> — setting a service area too broad (entire state) when you serve 3 cities dilutes your relevance signal for explicit city-level queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Neglecting "near me" optimization</strong> — GBP completeness, review volume, and accurate location data all influence "near me" results.</li>
          <li><strong>Not including location in title tags and H1s</strong> — location pages need "Plumbing Services in Austin, TX" in the title, not just "Plumbing Services."</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping LocalBusiness schema</strong> — structured data makes your location explicit to crawlers and can enhance your listing with address and hours in search results.</li>
        </ul>

